<br>
He was addressing the Jewish people only when He gave the 10 Commandments.  In fact, the entire OT Law was written just for the Israelites.  They had just come out of the land of Egypt.  They were use to having to worship many gods and having many idols.  The fact that right after He says &quot;you shall have no other gods before me&quot; He starts to talk about not making an idol, I think He is tying the two in together.  I think we have to look at the fact that God is giving these commandments to people who have been raised for generations upon generations being commanded to worship many gods.  He was talking directly to those people, so He would have been speaking in a way that they would understand best.<br>
<br>
Or else He could have simply been being poetic.  God is poetic ya know. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">**********************************************<br>
